---
/**
 * Affiliate Disclosure Policy Page
 *
 * FTC-compliant disclosure page explaining our affiliate relationships.
 * This page is linked from affiliate disclosure notices throughout the site.
 *
 * @module pages/disclosure
 */

import BaseLayout from '@/layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  meta={{
    title: 'Affiliate Disclosure Policy | StackHunt',
    description:
      'Learn about our affiliate relationships, how we make money, and our commitment to editorial independence.',
  }}
>
  <main class="min-h-screen bg-gradient-to-b from-zinc-950 to-zinc-900">
    <!-- Header -->
    <div class="border-b border-zinc-800 bg-zinc-950/50 backdrop-blur-sm">
      <div class="container mx-auto max-w-5xl px-4 py-8">
        <!-- Breadcrumbs -->
        <nav class="mb-4 flex items-center gap-2 text-sm text-zinc-500">
          <a href="/" class="hover:text-indigo-400 transition">Home</a>
          <span>/</span>
          <span class="text-zinc-400">Disclosure</span>
        </nav>

        <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold text-zinc-100 mb-3">Affiliate & Data Disclosure</h1>
        <p class="text-lg text-zinc-400 mb-4">
          Transparency is our core currency. This page explains how StackHunt earns revenue, how we
          generate our data, and the boundaries of our research.
        </p>
        <p class="text-sm text-zinc-600">Last Updated: February 2026</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="container mx-auto max-w-5xl px-4 py-12">
      <div class="grid gap-8 lg:grid-cols-[240px_1fr]">
        <!-- Table of Contents (Sticky) -->
        <aside class="hidden lg:block">
          <div class="sticky top-20">
            <h2 class="text-sm font-semibold text-zinc-400 mb-3">On This Page</h2>
            <nav class="space-y-2 text-sm">
              <a href="#revenue" class="block text-zinc-500 hover:text-indigo-400 transition"
                >How We Earn Revenue</a
              >
              <a href="#independence" class="block text-zinc-500 hover:text-indigo-400 transition"
                >Editorial Independence</a
              >
              <a href="#ai-integrity" class="block text-zinc-500 hover:text-indigo-400 transition"
                >AI & Data Integrity</a
              >
              <a href="#liability" class="block text-zinc-500 hover:text-indigo-400 transition"
                >Limitation of Liability</a
              >
              <a href="#research" class="block text-zinc-500 hover:text-indigo-400 transition"
                >How Our Research Works</a
              >
              <a href="#roadmap" class="block text-zinc-500 hover:text-indigo-400 transition"
                >Future Features</a
              >
            </nav>
          </div>
        </aside>

        <!-- Content -->
        <article
          class="prose prose-invert max-w-none prose-headings:text-zinc-100 prose-p:text-zinc-400 prose-a:text-indigo-400 hover:prose-a:text-indigo-300 prose-strong:text-zinc-200 prose-li:text-zinc-400 prose-h2:border-b prose-h2:border-zinc-800 prose-h2:pb-3 prose-h2:mb-6 prose-h2:scroll-mt-20 prose-h3:scroll-mt-20"
        >
          {/* Sections now have IDs for anchor links */}

          <h2 id="revenue">1. How We Earn Revenue</h2>

          <p>
            StackHunt is a free resource for software buyers. To keep the lights on, we participate
            in affiliate programs.
          </p>

          <p>
            <strong>The Mechanism:</strong> Some links to software tools on this site are tracking links.
            If you click one and upgrade to a paid plan, we may receive a commission.
          </p>

          <p>
            <strong>The Cost:</strong> This happens at <strong>zero cost to you</strong>. In many
            cases, our relationships allow us to unlock better deals or extended trials for you.
          </p>

          <h2 id="independence">2. The "Chinese Wall" (Editorial Independence)</h2>

          <p>
            <strong>Our revenue model does not dictate our rankings.</strong>
          </p>

          <ul>
            <li>
              <strong>Algorithm-First:</strong> Our "Fit Scores" and search rankings are generated programmatically
              based on feature matching, vector similarity, and user sentiment—not commission rates.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Universal Coverage:</strong> We list and review tools that have no affiliate program
              (like Trello or Notion's free tiers) with the exact same rigor as high-paying partners.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Negative Reviews:</strong> We do not censor "User Advocate" data. If a tool has
              a high "Frustration Score" on Reddit, we publish it, even if they are a partner.
            </li>
          </ul>

          <h2 id="ai-integrity">3. AI & Data Integrity</h2>

          <p>
            StackHunt is an <strong>AI-Powered Research Lab</strong>, not a manual blog.
          </p>

          <p>
            <strong>Synthesis, Not Generation:</strong> We use Artificial Intelligence to read thousands
            of documentation pages and synthesize community discussions. We do not let AI "invent" features.
          </p>

          <p>
            <strong>Pricing Accuracy:</strong> Pricing is volatile. While we employ a "Freshness Engine"
            to re-verify data regularly, we cannot guarantee real-time accuracy.
          </p>

          <p>
            <strong>Verification:</strong> Look for the "Verified on [Date]" badge on tool pages to gauge
            data freshness.
          </p>

          <h2 id="liability">4. Limitation of Liability</h2>

          <p>
            StackHunt provides data for <strong>informational and research purposes only</strong>.
            We are not a financial advisor, licensed software reseller, or professional services
            firm.
          </p>

          <p>
            <strong>Verification Required:</strong> Actual pricing, terms, and contract details should
            always be verified directly with the vendor before purchase.
          </p>

          <p>
            <strong>Optimization Suggestions:</strong> Any spend optimization suggestions, cost estimates,
            or "swap and save" recommendations are provided for illustrative purposes. Users are responsible
            for verifying all contract terms and pricing with third-party vendors before taking action.
          </p>

          <h3>Professional Service Disclaimer</h3>

          <p>
            <strong>Human-in-the-Loop:</strong> StackHunt provides spend optimization suggestions. StackHunt
            does not execute cancellations, upgrades, or contract changes autonomously. All financial
            actions must be reviewed and authorized by the User.
          </p>

          <p>
            <strong>No Fiduciary Duty:</strong> StackHunt is a software tool for data organization and
            analysis. StackHunt does not provide legal, tax, or financial advice. Users should consult
            with professional advisors before making significant structural or financial changes.
          </p>

          <p>
            <strong>Cap on Liability:</strong> In no event shall StackHunt's total liability exceed the
            amounts actually paid by you to StackHunt in the twelve (12) month period immediately preceding
            the event giving rise to such claim. For free tier users, liability is limited to direct damages
            not exceeding $100.
          </p>

          <h2 id="research">5. How Our Research Works</h2>

          <p>Our "Hunter" system performs comprehensive research on each tool:</p>

          <ol>
            <li>
              <strong>Automated Research</strong> - We run 12 parallel Google searches to gather information
              from multiple sources: official websites, professional reviews (G2, Capterra, Gartner),
              technical documentation, and community discussions (Reddit, HackerNews).
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>AI Analysis</strong> - Google's Gemini AI processes the search results in two passes:
              first to extract verifiable facts (pricing, features, platforms), then to synthesize contextual
              insights (who it's best for, common gotchas, tribal knowledge).
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Source Attribution</strong> - Every claim is linked to its source URL and classified
              by source type (official, editorial, community) and claim type (fact vs opinion).
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Human Verification</strong> - All AI-generated reviews are created as drafts and
              verified by our team before publishing. We correct errors and update outdated information.
            </li>
          </ol>

          <p>
            For complete details on our research methodology, see our
            <a href="/methodology" class="text-indigo-400 hover:text-indigo-300">Methodology page</a
            >.
          </p>

          <h3>Source Classification</h3>

          <p>We classify every source to help you assess credibility:</p>

          <ul>
            <li>
              <strong>Official sources</strong> - The tool's own website, documentation, or announcements
              (highest authority for factual claims)
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Editorial sources</strong> - Professional review sites (G2, Capterra) and tech publications
              (PCMag, TechRadar)
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Community sources</strong> - Reddit discussions, HackerNews threads, user forums
              (valuable for real-world experiences but subjective)
            </li>
          </ul>

          <h3>Fact vs Opinion</h3>

          <p>We clearly distinguish between verifiable facts and subjective opinions:</p>

          <ul>
            <li>
              <strong>Facts</strong> - Objectively verifiable information like pricing tiers, platform
              availability, feature lists, and integration support
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Opinions</strong> - Subjective assessments like user experience quality, customer
              support ratings, and value judgments from community discussions
            </li>
          </ul>

          <p>
            Every pro and con in our reviews includes metadata showing the source URL, source type,
            and whether it's a fact or opinion.
          </p>

          <h2>Data Freshness & Accuracy</h2>

          <p>
            Software products change frequently - pricing updates, new features launch, companies
            get acquired. We take data freshness seriously:
          </p>

          <ul>
            <li>
              <strong>Verification dates</strong> - Every tool page displays when the information was
              last verified, so you know how current the data is.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Stale data warnings</strong> - If data hasn't been verified in over 60 days, we
              display a clear warning banner.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Community reporting</strong> - Users can report outdated information, which automatically
              queues the tool for re-research.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Automatic updates</strong> - Popular tools are periodically re-researched to ensure
              accuracy.
            </li>
          </ul>

          <h2>Report Inaccuracies</h2>

          <p>Found something wrong or outdated? We want to know. When you report an inaccuracy:</p>

          <ol>
            <li>Your report is reviewed by our team</li>
            <li>If confirmed, we queue the tool for immediate re-research</li>
            <li>The tool is re-analyzed using our full 12-query research process</li>
            <li>Updated information is published with a new verification date</li>
          </ol>

          <p>
            We take accuracy seriously because our business depends on providing trustworthy
            recommendations.
          </p>

          <p>
            <a href="/corrections" class="text-indigo-400 hover:text-indigo-300">
              Submit a correction request
            </a>
          </p>

          <h2 id="roadmap">6. Future Features & Roadmap</h2>

          <p>
            StackHunt is evolving from a research platform into a comprehensive spend management
            tool. Future features may include:
          </p>

          <ul>
            <li>Subscription tracking and spend analysis</li>
            <li>Automated optimization recommendations</li>
            <li>Contract renewal alerts</li>
            <li>Team spend visibility dashboards</li>
          </ul>

          <p>
            <strong>Important:</strong> When these features launch, they will be governed by a separate
            Terms of Service agreement. All management features will require explicit user authorization
            before any financial actions are taken.
          </p>

          <h2>Summary Checklist</h2>

          <ul>
            <li><strong>Sticky Header:</strong> "Reader-supported" disclosure on every page</li>
            <li>
              <strong>Pricing Disclaimer:</strong> "Verify on official site" on pricing components
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Affiliate Links:</strong> All outbound affiliate links have <code
                >rel="nofollow sponsored"</code
              > attributes
            </li>
            <li><strong>Data Freshness:</strong> "Verified on [Date]" badges on tool pages</li>
            <li><strong>Liability Cap:</strong> Limited to amounts paid or $100 for free users</li>
          </ul>

          <hr class="my-8" />

          <p class="text-xs text-zinc-600">
            Last updated: {
              new Date().toLocaleDateString('en-US', { month: 'long', year: 'numeric' })
            }
          </p>
        </article>
      </div>
    </div>
  </main>

  <style>
    /* Smooth scroll for anchor links */
    html {
      scroll-behavior: smooth;
    }
  </style>
</BaseLayout>
